newsitem.title: SINGAPORE: Singapore gas oil trades higher, jet fuel slips.
newsitem.headline: Singapore gas oil trades higher, jet fuel slips.

text.p: Singapore gas oil traded higher Tuesday and traders said it is poised to surpass jet fuel values which remained pressured by large supplies and poor demand.

They said a European major sold 150,000 barrels of gas oil to a Singapore trader at $29.80 a barrel for October 23-27 lifting fob Singapore. This was 10 cents over the last cargo sold by the same major last week, which was a five-year high.

Traders said while front month physical jet fuel was offered below gas oil at $29.50, the first time the regrade has gone into a discount ahead of winter, forward jet prices continued to be offered higher at $30.75 for early November lifting.
Fuel oil prices were steady on healthy supplies despite firmer paper quotes, traders said.

Physical 180-centistoke cargoes for October were indicated at $122 per tonne but edged lower to $121. The same major oil companies emerged to offer October barrels. Chinese demand remained weak as current prices were too high, traders said. On the paper swaps, October was discussed at $120.25-$121.25 up from Monday's $119.50-$119.75.
Taiwan has awarded its tender to buy low sulphur fuel oil to a Japanese refiner at just under $142 per tonne for November to December delivery. --Singapore newsroom (65-870-3084)
